        {
            "id": "4c068924bae144e59ae08",
            "questionText": "A child on a swing is being pushed by an adult. The adult notices that the swing's amplitude increases significantly when pushing at a certain frequency. The swing has a natural frequency of $!$0.5\\,\\text{Hz}$!$. If the adult applies a periodic force with a frequency of $!$0.5\\,\\text{Hz}$!$, and the swing's motion is subject to damping due to friction, calculate the amplitude of the swing after $!$4\\,\\text{s}$!$, assuming the amplitude increases by $!$0.2\\,\\text{m}$!$ for each cycle without damping and that damping reduces the amplitude by $!$5\\%$!$ per cycle. Assume the initial amplitude is zero.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "7b6f942f1b6d4e3281090",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by identifying the phenomenon that occurs when the forcing frequency equals the natural frequency of the swing. Which concept does this situation illustrate?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "b3a7838d-1251-4a30-9fd8-7add8add3144"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\text{Damping}\\, $!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\text{Resonance}\\, $!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\text{Forced Oscillation without Resonance}\\, $!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "22c212bdb5854c8687014",
                    "stepText": "Great, now that we've recognized the phenomenon, determine the period of the swing using its driving frequency. Identify the formula that relates period $!$T$!$ and frequency $!$f$!$.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$T=\\frac{1}{f}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$T=f$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$T=f^2$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "529fed899f834b42a03f8",
                    "stepText": "Since the period $!$T$!$ is determined by the frequency, calculate the number of full driving cycles that occur in $!$4\\,\\text{s}$!$. Provide the numerical value.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "2"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "cycles",
                    "stepConcepts": [],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "3128ce9109454daaa8323",
                    "stepText": "Now, consider the effect of the push and damping on the amplitude for each cycle. Which iterative update rule correctly represents adding a push of $!$0.2\\,\\text{m}$!$ and then applying a damping factor of $!$0.95$!$ (i.e., a reduction of $!$5\\%$!$) per cycle?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$A_{n}=(A_{n-1}+0.2)\\times0.95$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$A_{n}=A_{n-1}+0.2\\times0.95$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$A_{n+1}=A_{n}\\times0.95+0.2$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "02329ddd98704a5d8fe37",
                    "stepText": "Let's apply the update rule for the first cycle. Starting with an initial amplitude $!$A_{0}=0$!$, calculate the amplitude $!$A_{1}$!$ at the end of the first cycle.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "0.19"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "m",
                    "stepConcepts": [],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "a45de248509144af97b06",
                    "stepText": "Now, using the iterative update rule, compute the amplitude $!$A_{2}$!$ after $!$4\\,\\text{s}$!$. Provide the final amplitude as a numerical value.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "0.37"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "m",
                    "stepConcepts": [],
                    "options": []
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "038b72d57bcd4a7684f69",
            "questionText": "An organ pipe that is open at both ends has a length of 1.5 m and the speed of sound in air is 343 m/s. Taking into account that open ends form antinodes, calculate the wavelength of the second harmonic produced by this pipe.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "21c8325b8e114553b6724",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by identifying the correct formula for the wavelength of a harmonic in an organ pipe that is open at both ends. Please select the proper formula.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "e9603b49-b438-4024-a0f2-1f8da3c929e7"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\lambda_n = \\frac{2L}{n}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\lambda_n = \\frac{L}{n}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\lambda_n = \\frac{4L}{n}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "3ccb0e36c0124babade6c",
                    "stepText": "Great, now that you've recalled the formula, determine the harmonic number (n) corresponding to the second harmonic produced by the pipe.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "2"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "001c90f1-aa84-454f-b15c-1c8c7c11db88",
                        "675c0c76-e5a0-48e5-b592-4f77f5c0bcc2"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "07aa5a0578724f009a7bf",
                    "stepText": "Now substitute the given length $!$L = 1.5\\,m$!$ and the harmonic number from the previous step into the wavelength formula to compute the wavelength. What value do you obtain?",
